    // Seed guides (INSERT IGNORE is idempotent — safe to re-run)
    $pdo->exec("INSERT IGNORE INTO guides (title, slug, description, content, image_url, category, cta_label, cta_link, position) VALUES
('The AI Automation Roadmap: A 12-Month Playbook for B2B Teams', 'ai-automation-roadmap-12-month-playbook', 'A step-by-step framework for auditing your operations, identifying high-ROI automation opportunities, and building a deployment plan that delivers measurable results within 90 days.', '<h2>Why Most Automation Projects Fail Before They Start</h2><p>Without a clear audit methodology, companies automate the wrong things first — spending budget on low-impact workflows while high-value bottlenecks remain manual. This playbook gives you the framework to avoid that mistake.</p><h2>Phase 1: The Operations Audit (Weeks 1-2)</h2><p>Start by mapping every workflow that involves more than 3 manual steps. Score each workflow on two dimensions: time cost per week and strategic impact. Automate high time-cost, high-impact workflows first.</p><h2>Phase 2: Tool Selection (Weeks 3-4)</h2><p>Match your workflow complexity to the right automation platform. Simple linear flows work well in Zapier or Make. Complex conditional logic with AI decision layers needs n8n or a custom agent framework.</p><h2>Phase 3: Build and Test (Weeks 5-10)</h2><p>Build one workflow at a time. Each workflow must have: a defined trigger, a logic layer, error handling with alerts, and an observable output. Do not move to the next workflow until the current one is stable for 2 weeks.</p><h2>Phase 4: Scale and Optimise (Weeks 11-12)</h2><p>Once your first batch of workflows are stable, introduce monitoring dashboards, set KPI targets, and begin the second round of automation based on updated audit data.</p>', 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1677442136019-21780ecad995?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=800', 'Strategy', 'Read the Playbook', '#', 0)");

    $pdo->exec("INSERT IGNORE INTO guides (title, slug, description, content, image_url, category, cta_label, cta_link, position) VALUES
('GEO vs SEO: The Complete Guide to Getting Your Brand Cited by AI', 'geo-vs-seo-complete-guide', 'Everything B2B marketing leaders need to know about Generative Engine Optimisation — how AI assistants select citations, what signals matter, and how to build a content strategy that wins in the AI answer era.', '<h2>The Search Landscape Has Changed</h2><p>When a buyer asks ChatGPT or Perplexity about the best automation agency, they receive a direct answer with 3-5 citations. If your brand is not cited, you do not exist in that decision. GEO is the discipline of ensuring you are always one of those citations.</p><h2>How AI Assistants Choose Citations</h2><p>LLMs are trained on web content and augmented with real-time retrieval. They prioritise: authoritative domains with strong topical depth, content that directly answers the query intent, structured markup that makes facts machine-readable, and content cited or linked to by other authoritative sources.</p><h2>The GEO Content Framework</h2><p>Step 1: Build entity authority. Create comprehensive topic clusters around your core service areas. Step 2: Use structured data markup (FAQ, HowTo, Article schemas). Step 3: Publish original research and data — LLMs cite statistics heavily. Step 4: Earn editorial citations from industry publications. Step 5: Monitor your citation rate using AI search tools quarterly.</p><h2>Measuring GEO Success</h2><p>Track: Brand mention rate in AI assistants (test manually monthly), citation share vs. competitors, and inbound traffic from AI-assisted research sessions (identifiable in GA4 by referral source patterns).</p>', 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1432888498266-38ffec3eaf0a?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=800', 'SEO', 'Read the Guide', '#', 1)");

    $pdo->exec("INSERT IGNORE INTO guides (title, slug, description, content, image_url, category, cta_label, cta_link, position) VALUES
('The AI Vendor Selection Scorecard: 7 Criteria Every Ops Leader Must Evaluate', 'ai-vendor-selection-scorecard', 'A structured evaluation framework for B2B operations leaders vetting AI automation partners. Score vendors across 7 weighted criteria and make a confident, data-backed selection decision.', '<h2>Why Vendor Selection Is the Highest-Stakes Decision in Your AI Journey</h2><p>Once you commit to an AI automation vendor, switching costs are high — your data, workflows, and team training are all tied to their platform. Getting the selection right the first time is worth slowing down to evaluate properly.</p><h2>The 7 Criteria Framework</h2><p><strong>1. Production Track Record (25 pts):</strong> Has the vendor deployed automations of similar complexity to yours in production — not demos, not pilots? Ask for 3 client references in your industry and call them.<br/><strong>2. Observability and Monitoring (20 pts):</strong> How do they detect, alert, and resolve failures in production workflows? Any serious vendor has real-time monitoring and defined SLAs.<br/><strong>3. Security and Data Governance (20 pts):</strong> Where is your data processed? Who has access? Can they provide a data processing agreement and SOC 2 documentation?<br/><strong>4. Integration Depth (15 pts):</strong> Do they have native integrations with your core stack (CRM, ERP, HRIS) or will everything require custom API work? Custom work = higher cost and longer timelines.<br/><strong>5. Team and Account Model (10 pts):</strong> Who will own your day-to-day relationship? What is the escalation path? Avoid vendors where your account manager is also the engineer.<br/><strong>6. Pricing Transparency (5 pts):</strong> Are costs fixed-scope or hourly? Are there hidden costs for infrastructure, API calls, or support tickets?<br/><strong>7. Exit and Portability (5 pts):</strong> If you leave, do you own all workflows and credentials? Is your automation logic locked into a proprietary platform?</p><h2>How to Score and Decide</h2><p>Score each vendor 1-5 on every criterion, then multiply by the weight. A score above 80/100 is a strong selection. Any criterion scored 1 should be treated as a disqualifier regardless of the total score.</p>', 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1454165804606-c3d57bc86b40?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=800', 'Strategy', 'Download the Scorecard', '#', 2)");

    $pdo->exec("INSERT IGNORE INTO guides (title, slug, description, content, image_url, category, cta_label, cta_link, position) VALUES
('The 90-Day Ops Transformation Playbook: From Manual to Automated', '90-day-ops-transformation-playbook', 'A week-by-week implementation guide for founders and COOs who want to automate their core operations without disrupting the business. Covers audit methodology, tool selection, build sprints, and go-live validation.', '<h2>Why 90 Days Is the Right Horizon</h2><p>Automation projects that try to do everything at once fail. Projects that are too narrowly scoped deliver marginal value. 90 days is long enough to automate 3-5 high-impact workflows and short enough to maintain executive sponsorship and team momentum.</p><h2>Month 1: The Audit (Weeks 1-4)</h2><p>Week 1-2: Map every operational workflow that touches more than 3 people or takes more than 4 hours per week. Create a simple spreadsheet with: workflow name, time cost per week, error rate, and strategic impact score (1-5).<br/>Week 3-4: Score workflows on an automation feasibility matrix. High time cost + high strategic impact + structured data = automate first. Low feasibility + low impact = skip entirely. Deliver an Automation Priority Report to leadership before Month 2 begins.</p><h2>Month 2: The Build (Weeks 5-10)</h2><p>Week 5-6: Select your tool stack based on workflow complexity. Simple linear flows: Zapier or Make. Complex conditional logic with AI: n8n or custom agent. Week 7-10: Build workflows in order of priority. Each workflow needs: trigger definition, logic layer, error handling with alerts, a test suite with 20+ edge cases, and a defined human escalation path. Do not move to the next workflow until the current one passes QA for 5 consecutive test runs.</p><h2>Month 3: Launch and Validate (Weeks 11-12)</h2><p>Week 11: Soft launch with real data on a shadow pipeline. Compare automated outputs against manual baseline for 5 business days. Week 12: Full go-live. Set KPI targets (time saved, error rate, throughput). Schedule a 30-day and 60-day performance review with leadership. Build a monitoring dashboard that surfaces anomalies before they escalate.</p>', 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1611532736597-de2d4265fba3?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=800', 'Operations', 'Read the Playbook', '#', 3)"  );

